com.duprasville.guava.probably

Class CuckooFilter<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.duprasville.guava.probably.CuckooFilter<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of objects that the CuckooFilter accepts
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    ProbabilisticFilter<T>, Serializable

    @Beta
public final class CuckooFilter<T>
extends Object
implements ProbabilisticFilter<T>, Serializable
    A Cuckoo filter for instances of T. A Cuckoo filter offers an approximate containment test with one-sided error: if it claims that an element is contained in it, this might be in error, but if it claims that an element is not contained in it, then this is definitely true.

    The false positive probability (FPP) of a cuckoo filter is defined as the probability that mightContain(Object) will erroneously return true for an object that has not actually been put in the CuckooFilter.

    Cuckoo filters are serializable. They also support a more compact serial representation via the writeTo(java.io.OutputStream) and readFrom(java.io.InputStream, com.google.common.hash.Funnel<T>) methods. Both serialized forms will continue to be supported by future versions of this library. However, serial forms generated by newer versions of the code may not be readable by older versions of the code (e.g., a serialized cuckoo filter generated today may not be readable by a binary that was compiled 6 months ago).

    ref: Cuckoo Filter: Practically Better Than Bloom Bin Fan, David G. Andersen, Michael Kaminsky†, Michael D. Mitzenmacher‡ Carnegie Mellon University, †Intel Labs, ‡Harvard University https://www.cs.cmu.edu/~dga/papers/cuckoo-conext2014.pdf

    Author:
    Brian Dupras, Alex Beal

    • Method Detail

      • putAll

        public boolean putAll(CuckooFilter<T> that)
        Combines this cuckoo filter with another cuckoo filter by performing multiset sum of the underlying data. The mutations happen to this instance. Callers must ensure the cuckoo filters are appropriately sized to avoid saturating them.
        Parameters:
        that - The cuckoo filter to combine this cuckoo filter with. It is not mutated.
        Returns:
        true of the filters are successfully summed, false otherwise.
        Throws:
        IllegalArgumentException - if isCompatible(that) == false

      • put

        @CheckReturnValue
public boolean put(T object)
        Puts an object into this CuckooFilter. Ensures that subsequent invocations of mightContain(Object) with the same object will always return true.
        Specified by:
        put in interface ProbabilisticFilter<T>
        Returns:
        true if object has been successfully added to the filter. false if object was not added to the filter, as would be the case when the filter gets saturated. This may occur even if actualInsertions < expectedInsertions. e.g. If object has already been added 2*b times to the filter, a subsequent attempt will fail.

      • delete

        @CheckReturnValue
public boolean delete(T object)
        Deletes object from this CuckooFilter. object must been previously added to the filter. Deleting an object that hasn't been added to the filter may put the filter in an inconsistent state causing it to return false negative responses from get(t).

        If false is returned, this is definitely an indication that either this invocation or a previous invocation have called delete(t) without a matching invocation of put(t). This condition is always an error and the this CuckooFilter can no longer be relied upon to return correct false responses from get(t).

        Returns:
        true if object was successfully deleted from the filter.

      • size

        public long size()
        Returns the number of inserted items currently represented in the filter.

      • expectedFpp

        @CheckReturnValue
public double expectedFpp()
        Returns the probability that mightContain(Object) will erroneously return true for an object that has not actually been put in the CuckooFilter.

        Ideally, this number should be close to the fpp parameter passed in create(Funnel, int, double), or smaller. If it is significantly higher, it is usually the case that too many objects (more than expected) have been put in the CuckooFilter, degenerating it.

        Specified by:
        expectedFpp in interface ProbabilisticFilter<T>
        Returns:
        the probability that ProbabilisticFilter.mightContain(Object) will erroneously return true for an object that has not actually been put in the filter.

      • isCompatible

        @CheckReturnValue
public boolean isCompatible(CuckooFilter<T> that)
        Determines whether a given cuckoo filter is compatible with this cuckoo filter. For two cuckoo filters to be compatible, they must:

        • not be the same instance
        • have tables of the same dimensions
        • have the same strategy
        • have equal funnels
          Parameters:
          that - The cuckoo filter to check for compatibility.

        • create

          @CheckReturnValue
public static <T> CuckooFilter<T> create(com.google.common.hash.Funnel<? super T> funnel,
                                          int expectedInsertions,
                                          double fpp)
          Creates a CuckooFilter with the expected number of insertions and expected false positive probability.

          Note that overflowing a CuckooFilter with significantly more objects than specified, will result in its saturation causing put(t) to reject new additions.

          The constructed CuckooFilter<T> will be serializable if the provided Funnel<T> is.

          It is recommended that the funnel be implemented as a Java enum. This has the benefit of ensuring proper serialization and deserialization, which is important since equals(java.lang.Object) also relies on object identity of funnels.

          Parameters:
          funnel - the funnel of T's that the constructed CuckooFilter<T> will use
          expectedInsertions - the number of expected insertions to the constructed CuckooFilter<T>; must be positive
          fpp - the desired false positive probability (must be positive and less than 1.0)
          Returns:
          a CuckooFilter

        • writeTo

          public void writeTo(OutputStream out)
             throws IOException
          Writes this CuckooFilter to an output stream, with a custom format (not Java serialization). This has been measured to save at least 400 bytes compared to regular serialization.

          Use readFrom(InputStream, Funnel) to reconstruct the written CuckooFilter.

          Throws:
          IOException

        • readFrom

          @CheckReturnValue
public static <T> CuckooFilter<T> readFrom(InputStream in,
                                            com.google.common.hash.Funnel<T> funnel)
                                throws IOException
          Reads a byte stream, which was written by writeTo(OutputStream), into a CuckooFilter<T>.

          The Funnel to be used is not encoded in the stream, so it must be provided here. Warning: the funnel provided must behave identically to the one used to populate the original Cuckoo filter!

          Throws:
          IOException - if the InputStream throws an IOException, or if its data does not appear to be a CuckooFilter serialized using the writeTo(OutputStream) method.
